tailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n-Open a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n-Enter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\".\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following. If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nPolicy Change &gt;&gt; Authorization Policy Change - Success","false_positives":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"uuid":"67B5E8CB-722B-1014-89C5-A77438A7C06C","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuthorization Policy Change records events related to changes in user rights, such as create a token object.","finding_details":"Tool: cpe:/a:niwc:scc:5.14\nTime         : 2026-04-01T11:52:15\nResult: failRule Result     : Fail\nCriteria        : false (All child tests must be true. (AND))\nCriteria        :   false (One or more child tests must be true. (OR))\nTest            :     false (Audit - Audit Policy Change - Success only)\nResult Analysis :          authorization_policy_change = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'equals' compared to 'AUDIT_SUCCESS' \nTest            :     false (Audit - Audit Policy Change - Success and Failure)\nResult Analysis :          authorization_policy_change = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'equals' compared to 'AUDIT_SUCCESS_FAILURE' \n"},{"security_override_guidance":"","group_title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","third_party_tools":"","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit Privilege Use - Sensitive Privilege Use failures.","rule_id":"SV-253328r958732","weight"